  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "LEWIS FAGEN",
    "text": "I wanted to say that I know Rena over 55 years. We lived on the same block. We attended the same school. And right when I met her, I decided that I'm going to marry her one day, which I did after the war, after we both survived in Schindler's camp in Brunnlitz. I only wanted to say that we are both very fortunate. We were very rare specimens of survivors, who both had parents who survived with us. And our children had grandparents, which is rare for the survivors. We have two-- we were blessed with two wonderful sons and six granddaughters, starting from ages of six months all the way up to 17 years. And all in all, we had a happy post-war life. [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] Otherwise, there isn't much left to say. [PAUSES FOR 6 SECONDS] We are looking forward to our retirement in Florida for many, many years to come. We enjoy every minute of it. [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] We also have a little pied-a-terre up north. We spend time seeing our grandchildren and children, traveling to Boston to see our other son.",
